    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Unions have faced political opposition because some believe they can hinder economic growth and competitiveness. Critics argue that unions can lead to higher labor costs, which may result in businesses relocating to countries with cheaper labor. They also contend that unions can stifle innovation by prioritizing job security over adapting to new technologies. Additionally, some argue that unions can create an imbalance in negotiations, favoring workers over employers, potentially leading to reduced investment and job creation. These arguments are often used to justify policies that limit union power and influence in the US.",
      "source": "target",
